The numeric types.

Scala's numeric types are thin wrappers over java virtual machine primitives. Their sizes and ranges are exactly what the machine provides. Byte is eight bits. Short is sixteen. Integer is thirty-two bits, ranging roughly plus or minus two point one billion, and it is the default for a whole-number literal. Long is sixty-four bits — to write a long literal, add the suffix capital L. Float is thirty-two-bit single-precision floating point, with the suffix lowercase f. Double is sixty-four-bit double-precision, and it is the default for a decimal literal. And for numbers without bounds, there is big-int for arbitrary-precision integers and big-decimal for exact decimal arithmetic, both constructed from a quoted string.

Three things you have to remember when working with these.

First, the default literal types. A whole-number literal is an integer, not a long. A decimal literal is a double, not a float. Add the suffix capital L or lowercase f to override.

Second, overflow is silent. Adding past the maximum of an integer wraps around to a large negative number, and the compiler will not warn you. Reach for long when magnitudes can grow, or big-int when they can grow without bound.

Third, floating point is not decimal. Zero point one plus zero point two does not give exactly zero point three in a double — you get a tiny trailing error, exactly as in every other language that uses the i-e-e-e seven fifty-four standard. For money, or any context where exact decimal arithmetic matters, reach for big-decimal.

One more detail on conversions. Promotion is one-directional. A small integer widens to a long or a double automatically, but a long does not narrow back to an integer on its own — you have to call to-int explicitly, and accept that you may lose information.
